{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"24092bb1b59da49c8f3be1954bb465109988a8f7d39734a8f19a5a7e1bf771ee","slug":"pages.m09-probability-rules-4-of-11","location":"/pages/106-m09-probability-rules-4-of-11.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Probability Rules (4 of 11)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"thumbnail":"/build/lbd004-300d0192c000996a0b60e324120aa2c5.gif","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"106-m09-probability-rules-4-of-11.md","url":"/build/106-m09-probability--ffdb2b94d59ed93943f049931c0dbf86.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"PdzCXlKctS"}],"key":"ilf4I5Xubd"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- Apply probability rules in order to find the likelihood of an event.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"krU5ctGAIW"}],"key":"OBMfMrQ3DG"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Rule 4: The Addition Rule for Disjoint Events","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"gi46JjZQJ9"}],"key":"huzHcBqMMI"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"*The Addition Rule for Disjoint Events: If A and B are disjoint events, then P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B).*","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"PA4LUZdv92"}],"key":"nX48V7TmHL"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Comment","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"c2DVxq428V"}],"identifier":"comment","label":"Comment","html_id":"comment","implicit":true,"key":"c7E3GYKj3i"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When dealing with probabilities, the word “or” will always be associated with the operation of addition; hence the name of this rule, “The Addition Rule.”","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"ymaaBXzN5Y"}],"key":"nBY6eLL8Vd"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"IxbpmGw5Yx"}],"key":"vQOjJsXkPX"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"Recall the blood type example:\n\n```{figure} images/image011.gif\n:alt: Data given in \"Blood Type: Probability\" Format: O: 0.44; A: 0.42; B: 0.10; AB: 0.04;\n\nData given in \"Blood Type: Probability\" Format: O: 0.44; A: 0.42; B: 0.10; AB: 0.04;\n```\n\nHere is some additional information:\n\n* A person with type *A* can donate blood to a person with type *A* or *AB.*\n\n* A person with type *B* can donate blood to a person with type *B* or *AB.*\n\n* A person with type *AB* can donate blood to a person with type *AB* only.\n\n* A person with type *O* blood can donate to anyone.\n\nWhat is the probability that a randomly chosen person is a potential donor for a person with blood type A?\n\nFrom the information given, we know that being a potential donor for a person with blood type A means having blood type A or O. We therefore need to find P(A or O). Since the events A and O are disjoint, we can use the addition rule for disjoint events to get: P(A or O) = P(A) + P(O) = .42 + .44 = .86. It is easy to see why adding the probability actually makes sense. If 42% of the population has blood type A and 44% of the population has blood type O, then 42% + 44% = 86% of the population has either blood type A or O, and thus are potential donors to a person with blood type A. This reasoning about why the addition rule makes sense can be visualized using the pie chart below:\n\n```{figure} images/image017a.gif\n:alt: A pie chart titled \"Blood Types.\" Type A takes up 42% of the pie chart, and type O takes up 44%. Together, as A or O, they take up 86% of the pie chart.\n\nA pie chart titled \"Blood Types.\" Type A takes up 42% of the pie chart, and type O takes up 44%. Together, as A or O, they take up 86% of the pie chart.\n```","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"key":"mVlnHX6z66"}],"key":"oBuOn3cAS8"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"LDFN89R4tc"}],"key":"r45qjEqbEb"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"key":"hF3IBiAOGN"}],"key":"we8XBU7WUU"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learn By Doing","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"E1KuxZFwDi"}],"identifier":"learn-by-doing","label":"Learn By Doing","html_id":"learn-by-doing","implicit":true,"key":"jehLPjR5VA"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So far we have introduced the addition rule for the special case in which the events being considered are disjoint. The purpose of this activity is to make you aware of the danger in wrongly using the addition rule for disjoint events in cases where the events are actually not disjoint. Consider the blood type example again.","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"key":"xiPI1vHgXw"}],"key":"qcuqGhuleq"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Recall the blood type example:","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"key":"Bkm7PdTabK"}],"key":"x8r13tomjG"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/lbd004-300d0192c000996a0b60e324120aa2c5.gif","alt":"Data given in \"Blood Type: Probability\" Format: O: 0.44; A: 0.42; B: 0.10; AB: 0.04;","key":"mkso2rql5Z","urlSource":"images/lbd004.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":60,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Data given in “Blood Type: Probability” Format: O: 0.44; A: 0.42; B: 0.10; AB: 0.04;","position":{"start":{"line":60,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"key":"I2PNFLKOOK"}],"key":"pJbEqyOcmZ"}],"key":"GsGodqluBG"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"PIWDTVrg5k"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":63,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"with the following additional information:","position":{"start":{"line":63,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"key":"RF8IOhxRZQ"}],"key":"OXFN8wz3fc"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A person with type ","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"d6tz2lIj7K"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"IHw0JyYZNi"}],"key":"M305ctREEX"},{"type":"text","value":" can donate blood to a person with type ","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"PzY2Su5mck"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"jCK0dJ5mrw"}],"key":"KfPb7E5sKC"},{"type":"text","value":" or ","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"NUIQCfQZSd"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"AB","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"YA8lMrcEex"}],"key":"eLFWRzHlur"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"QCN7UswTgG"}],"key":"AmDcPDYt2k"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A person with type ","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"NNaYGTigYr"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"B","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"PWYTYWycGq"}],"key":"D7b0pjk7yY"},{"type":"text","value":" can donate blood to a person with type ","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"rSkTMumlpH"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"B","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"RQzZ3Vu95p"}],"key":"bmcQerSPRb"},{"type":"text","value":" or ","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"fn5ZZeUFBw"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"t