{"start":{"line":73,"column":1},"end":{"line":73,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Suppose that there are two patients who are each in need of a blood donation. Patient 1 has blood type A and patient 2 has blood type B. Consider the following events:","position":{"start":{"line":73,"column":1},"end":{"line":73,"column":1}},"key":"G3n70kuVgf"}],"key":"HbRW9ohO6i"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"D1—a randomly chosen person can be a donor for patient 1.","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"key":"G7VTvZZMaI"}],"key":"sRcbz3uZQZ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":77,"column":1},"end":{"line":77,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"D2—a randomly chosen person can be a donor for patient 2.","position":{"start":{"line":77,"column":1},"end":{"line":77,"column":1}},"key":"xkO0NxXRdl"}],"key":"pkh3tSBFd2"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":79,"column":1},"end":{"line":79,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We are interested in finding the probability that a randomly chosen person can be a donor for patient 1 or patient 2. In other words, we are interested in finding P(D1 or D2).","position":{"start":{"line":79,"column":1},"end":{"line":79,"column":1}},"key":"s0hyowt9mB"}],"key":"bDOy1gA9T9"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"fdW95NPAkx"}],"key":"AN95PbkhtR"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Sectionnest**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":82,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"key":"FgeI33zfEL"}],"key":"IoWzCIL7FU"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"uvaMS9nmOR"}],"key":"fnVKTBOsYF"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Sectionnest**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":90,"column":1}},"key":"YkQ33F5wuu"}],"key":"z97nWfCnik"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"JrDnjipllN"}],"key":"mXY38afPwu"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Sectionnest**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":96,"column":1}},"key":"t4QxwPqCO1"}],"key":"w5aq4B8usb"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As we mentioned earlier, later on in this module we will establish a more general Addition Rule that applies even when two events are not disjoint.","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"pJqzgo54rR"}],"key":"XLewiDY4E4"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Comment","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"key":"Oukq1lrkTF"}],"identifier":"comment","label":"Comment","html_id":"comment-1","implicit":true,"key":"U1A2MSBJY2"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":103,"column":1},"end":{"line":103,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The Addition Rule for Disjoint Events can naturally be extended to more than two disjoint events. Let’s take three, for example. If A, B and C are three disjoint events,","position":{"start":{"line":103,"column":1},"end":{"line":103,"column":1}},"key":"BwEqGh19Zc"}],"key":"TXSqy8r2h7"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/build/image018-043d14e3ab4267a649added30a1f92a6.gif","alt":"A Venn Diagram showing 3 disjoint events. As usual there is a gray box showing the entire sample space. Inside this gray box are three completely separate circles. The first circle is for the occurrences in A, the second for occurrences in B, and the third for occurrences in C.","key":"D05YPOsaqa","urlSource":"images/image018.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":108,"column":1},"end":{"line":108,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A Venn Diagram showing 3 disjoint events. As usual there is a gray box showing the entire sample space. Inside this gray box are three completely separate circles. The first circle is for the occurrences in A, the second for occurrences in B, and the third for occurrences in C.","position":{"start":{"line":108,"column":1},"end":{"line":108,"column":1}},"key":"IjceGEdNpe"}],"key":"igK5RvOXhV"}],"key":"MrzOxlQVnh"}],"enumerator":"2","key":"R8RwxCYqSR"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"then P(A or B or C) = P(A) + P(B) + P(C). The rule is the same for any number of disjoint events.","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"b5nKgBE2QQ"}],"key":"mQlDBCDGkE"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"rlTR7DstG7"}],"key":"Hmmdds0mzf"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Learn By Doing**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":114,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"key":"MdULAyFWpw"}],"key":"Mxda4luN97"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We are now done with the first version of the Addition Rule (the version restricted to disjoint events) and we are ready to move on to rule 5. As mentioned before, the general version of the Addition Rule will be presented after rule 5.","position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"key":"GNE5en7JwO"}],"key":"ZCFT4TTDt0"}],"key":"d57GOTFrw2"}],"key":"h9XtPpc4yy"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Probability Rules (3 of 11)","url":"/pages/m09-probability-rules-3-of-11","group":"Unit 4: Probability"},"next":{"title":"Probability Rules (5 of 11)","url":"/pages/m09-probability-rules-5-of-11","group":"Unit 4: Probability"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3001"}